AUDIO: 'speed. So, start with why agents feel slow. To write a single token, a large model fires a full pass through every parameter. For V4 Pro, that is 1.6 trillion of them for one word. At scale,'

[01:53] [scene:explanation]
VISUAL: "Guess a block. Verify it once." text on screen, showing a draft model proposing tokens and V4 verifying.
AUDIO: 'the GPU spends more time shuffling memory than doing math. So, the chip sits half idle just waiting for the next token to fall out. Speculative decoding breaks that pattern. A small, fast draft model guesses a whole block of tokens'

[02:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'ahead. Then, the big model checks the entire block in a single pass, verifying five guesses for nearly the cost of one. Every guess it accepts is a token you got almost for free. And none of this is brand new, by the way. Google and'

[02:19] [scene:explanation]
VISUAL: "Wrong guesses, thrown out." text on screen, demonstrating accepted and rejected tokens in a code snippet.
AUDIO: 'DeepMind published speculative decoding back in 2023. And every big lab quietly runs some version of it. What is new is DeepSeek shipping a production-grade one out in the open with acceptance rates that blow past those first attempts. And'

[02:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'it cannot quietly lower your quality. The verifier uses rejection sampling, which keeps the final output mathematically identical to normal decoding. Wrong guesses are thrown away. You only ever keep the tokens the real'

[02:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'model would have written anyway. You just get them sooner. It all reduces to one equation. Latency equals draft time plus verify time divided by how many tokens you accept each cycle. So, there are exactly three ways to win. Draft'

[02:57] [scene:explanation]
VISUAL: "Two old tricks, one flaw each." text on screen, comparing Eagle (autoregressive) and DFlash (parallel) methods.
AUDIO: 'faster, draft better, or verify smarter. DeepSpark, unusually, pulls all three levers at once. Older methods could only pull one. Autoregressive drafters, like Eagle, guess accurately but slow down as the'

[03:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'block grows. Parallel drafters, like Flash, are cheap, but they guess every token blind to its neighbors. So, the back of the block rots and gets rejected. They call it suffix decay. DeepSpark\'s first move is to take both'

[03:23] [scene:explanation]
VISUAL: "One nudge, holds the block." text on screen, illustrating DSpark's Markov head improving acceptance rates.
AUDIO: 'sides. A fast parallel backbone proposes the whole block at once. Then, a tiny sequential head, low-rank Markov, adds one quick correction, nudging each token based on the one right before it. Cheap'

[03:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'like parallel, accurate like sequential. Picture it midline. The block proposes the word return, and the little head instantly boosts result while pushing down problem. That single nudge keeps acceptance high all the way to the end'

[03:48] [scene:explanation]
VISUAL: "The scheduler is free." text on screen, showing GPU verify blocks and scheduler predictions.
AUDIO: 'of the block, exactly where the older methods used to bleed their speed. The second move stops wasted work. A confidence head scores how likely each guess is to survive, and a hardware-aware scheduler reads the GPU'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL: 
AUDIO: 'load. When the chips are idle, verify more tokens. When they are slammed, trim down to only the confident ones. Speed that bends to the moment. The third move makes the scheduler itself free. Zero-overhead scheduling runs a step'

